\title{Git Cleanup}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{"Safely analyzes and cleans up local git branches and worktrees by categorizing them as merged, squash-merged, superseded, or active work."}

\subtree{
\title{Git Cleanup}
\p{Safely clean up accumulated git worktrees and local branches by categorizing them into: safely deletable (merged), potentially related (similar themes), and active work (keep).}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\ul{
\li{When the user has accumulated many local branches and worktrees}
\li{When branches have been merged but not cleaned up locally}
\li{When remote branches have been deleted but local tracking branches remain}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{When NOT to Use}
\ul{
\li{Do not use for remote branch management (this is local cleanup only)}
\li{Do not use for repository maintenance tasks like gc or prune}
\li{Not designed for headless or non-interactive automation (requires user confirmations at two gates)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Core Principle: SAFETY FIRST}
\p{\strong{Never delete anything without explicit user confirmation.} This skill uses a gated workflow where users must approve each step before any destructive action.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Critical Implementation Notes}
\subtree{
\title{Squash-Merged Branches Require Force Delete}
\p{\strong{IMPORTANT:} \code{\startverb git branch -d\stopverb} will ALWAYS fail for squash-merged branches because git cannot detect that the work was incorporated. This is expected behavior, not an error.}

\p{When you identify a branch as squash-merged:}

\ul{
\li{Plan to use \code{\startverb git branch -D\stopverb} (force delete) from the start}
\li{Do NOT try \code{\startverb git branch -d\stopverb} first and then ask again for \code{\startverb -D\stopverb} - this wastes user confirmations}
\li{In the confirmation step, show \code{\startverb git branch -D\stopverb} for squash-merged branches}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Group Related Branches BEFORE Categorization}
\p{\strong{MANDATORY:} Before categorizing individual branches, group them by name prefix:}

\pre{\startverb
# Extract common prefixes from branch names
# e.g., feature/auth-*, feature/api-*, fix/login-*
\stopverb}

\p{Branches sharing a prefix (e.g., \code{\startverb feature/api\stopverb}, \code{\startverb feature/api-v2\stopverb}, \code{\startverb feature/api-refactor\stopverb}) are almost certainly related iterations. Analyze them as a group:}

\ol{
\li{Find the oldest and newest by commit date}
\li{Check if newer branches contain commits from older ones}
\li{Check which PRs merged work from each}
\li{Determine if older branches are superseded}
}

\p{Present related branches together with a clear recommendation, not scattered across categories.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Thorough PR History Investigation}
\p{Don't rely on simple keyword matching. For \code{\startverb [gone]\stopverb} branches:}

\pre{\startverb
# 1. Get the branch's commits that aren't in default branch
git log --oneline "$default_branch".."$branch"

# 2. Search default branch for PRs that incorporated this work
# Search by: branch name, commit message keywords, PR numbers
git log --oneline "$default_branch" | grep -iE "(branch-name|keyword|#[0-9]+)"

# 3. For related branch groups, trace which PRs merged which work
git log --oneline "$default_branch" | grep -iE "(#[0-9]+)" | head -20
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Workflow}
\subtree{
\title{Phase 1: Comprehensive Analysis}
\p{Gather ALL information upfront before any categorization:}

\pre{\startverb
# Get default branch name
default_branch=$(git symbolic-ref refs/remotes/origin/HEAD \
  2>/dev/null | sed 's@^refs/remotes/origin/@@' || echo "main")

# Protected branches - never analyze or delete
protected='^(main|master|develop|release/.*)$'

# List all local branches with tracking info
git branch -vv

# List all worktrees
git worktree list

# Fetch and prune to sync remote state
git fetch --prune

# Get merged branches (into default branch)
git branch --merged "$default_branch"

# Get recent PR merge history (squash-merge detection)
git log --oneline "$default_branch" | grep -iE "#[0-9]+" | head -30

# For EACH non-protected branch, get unique commits and sync status
for branch in $(git branch --format='%(refname:short)' \
  | grep -vE "$protected"); do
  echo "=== $branch ==="
  echo "Commits not in $default_branch:"
  git log --oneline "$default_branch".."$branch" 2>/dev/null \
    | head -5
  echo "Commits not pushed to remote:"
  git log --oneline "origin/$branch".."$branch" 2>/dev/null \
    | head -5 || echo "(no remote tracking)"
done
\stopverb}

\pre{\startverb
**Note on branch names:** Git branch names can contain characters that break shell expansion. Always quote `"$branch"` in commands.
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 2: Group Related Branches}
\p{\strong{Do this BEFORE individual categorization.}}

\p{Identify branch groups by shared prefixes:}

\pre{\startverb
# List branches and extract prefixes
git branch --format='%(refname:short)' | sed 's/-[^-]*$//' | sort | uniq -c | sort -rn
\stopverb}

\p{For each group with 2+ branches:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Compare commit histories} - Which branches contain commits from others?}
\li{\strong{Find merge evidence} - Which PRs incorporated work from this group?}
\li{\strong{Identify the "final" branch} - Usually the most recent or most complete}
\li{\strong{Mark superseded branches} - Older iterations whose work is in main or in a newer branch}
}

\p{\strong{SUPERSEDED requires evidence, not just shared prefix:}}

\ul{
\li{A PR merged the work into main, OR}
\li{A newer branch contains all commits from the older branch}
\li{Name prefix alone is NOT sufficient — similarly named branches may contain independent work}
}

\p{Example analysis for \code{\startverb feature/api-*\stopverb} branches:}

\pre{\startverb
### Related Branch Group: feature/api-*

| Branch | Commits | PR Merged | Status |
|--------|---------|-----------|--------|
| feature/api | 12 | #29 (initial API) | Superseded - work in main |
| feature/api-v2 | 8 | #45 (API improvements) | Superseded - work in main |
| feature/api-refactor | 5 | #67 (refactor) | Superseded - work in main |
| feature/api-final | 4 | None found | Superseded by above PRs |

**Recommendation:** All 4 branches can be deleted - work incorporated via PRs #29, #45, #67
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 3: Categorize Remaining Branches}
\p{For branches NOT in a related group, categorize individually:}

\pre{\startverb
Is branch merged into default branch?
├─ YES → SAFE_TO_DELETE (use -d)
└─ NO → Is tracking a remote?
        ├─ YES → Remote deleted? ([gone])
        │        ├─ YES → Was work squash-merged? (check main for PR)
        │        │        ├─ YES → SQUASH_MERGED (use -D)
        │        │        └─ NO → REMOTE_GONE (needs review)
        │        └─ NO → Local ahead of remote? (check: git log origin/<branch>..<branch>)
        │                ├─ YES (has output) → UNPUSHED_WORK (keep)
        │                └─ NO (empty output) → SYNCED_WITH_REMOTE (keep)
        └─ NO → Has unique commits?
                ├─ YES → LOCAL_WORK (keep)
                └─ NO → SAFE_TO_DELETE (use -d)
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Category definitions:}}

\pre{\startverb
| Category | Meaning | Delete Command |
|----------|---------|----------------|
| SAFE_TO_DELETE | Merged into default branch | `git branch -d` |
| SQUASH_MERGED | Work incorporated via squash merge | `git branch -D` |
| SUPERSEDED | Part of a group, work verified in main via PR or in newer branch | `git branch -D` |
| REMOTE_GONE | Remote deleted, work NOT found in main | Review needed |
| UNPUSHED_WORK | Has commits not pushed to remote | Keep |
| LOCAL_WORK | Untracked branch with unique commits | Keep |
| SYNCED_WITH_REMOTE | Up to date with remote | Keep |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 4: Dirty State Detection}
\p{Check ALL worktrees and current directory for uncommitted changes:}

\pre{\startverb
# For each worktree path
git -C <worktree-path> status --porcelain

# For current directory
git status --porcelain
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Display warnings prominently:}}

\pre{\startverb
WARNING: ../proj-auth has uncommitted changes:
  M  src/auth.js
  ?? new-file.txt

These changes will be LOST if you remove this worktree.
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{GATE 1: Present Complete Analysis}
\p{Present everything in ONE comprehensive view. Group related branches together:}

\pre{\startverb
## Git Cleanup Analysis

### Related Branch Groups

**Group: feature/api-* (4 branches)**
| Branch | Status | Evidence |
|--------|--------|----------|
| feature/api | Superseded | Work merged in PR #29 |
| feature/api-v2 | Superseded | Work merged in PR #45 |
| feature/api-refactor | Superseded | Work merged in PR #67 |
| feature/api-final | Superseded | Older iteration, diverged |

Recommendation: Delete all 4 (work is in main)

---

### Individual Branches

**Safe to Delete (merged with -d)**
| Branch | Merged Into |
|--------|-------------|
| fix/typo | main |

**Safe to Delete (squash-merged, requires -D)**
| Branch | Merged As |
|--------|-----------|
| feature/login | PR #42 |

**Needs Review ([gone] remotes, no PR found)**
| Branch | Last Commit |
|--------|-------------|
| experiment/old | abc1234 "WIP something" |

**Keep (active work)**
| Branch | Status |
|--------|--------|
| wip/new-feature | 5 unpushed commits |

### Worktrees
| Path | Branch | Status |
|------|--------|--------|
| ../proj-auth | feature/auth | STALE (merged) |

---

**Summary:**
- 4 related branches (feature/api-*) - recommend delete all
- 1 merged branch - safe to delete
- 1 squash-merged branch - safe to delete
- 1 needs review
- 1 to keep

Which would you like to clean up?
\stopverb}

\p{Use AskUserQuestion with clear options:}

\ul{
\li{Delete all recommended (groups + merged + squash-merged)}
\li{Delete specific groups/categories}
\li{Let me pick individual branches}
}

\p{\strong{Do not proceed until user responds.}}
}

\subtree{
\title{GATE 2: Final Confirmation with Exact Commands}
\p{Show the EXACT commands that will run, with correct flags:}

\pre{\startverb
I will execute:

# Merged branches (safe delete)
git branch -d fix/typo

# Squash-merged branches (force delete - work is in main via PRs)
git branch -D feature/login
git branch -D feature/api
git branch -D feature/api-v2
git branch -D feature/api-refactor
git branch -D feature/api-final

# Worktrees
git worktree remove ../proj-auth

Confirm? (yes/no)
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{IMPORTANT:} This is the ONLY confirmation needed for deletion. Do not add extra confirmations if \code{\startverb -D\stopverb} is required.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 5: Execute}
\p{Run each deletion as a \strong{separate command} so partial failures don't block remaining deletions. Report the result of each:}

\pre{\startverb
git branch -d fix/typo
git branch -D feature/login
git branch -D feature/api
git branch -D feature/api-v2
git branch -D feature/api-refactor
git branch -D feature/api-final
git worktree remove ../proj-auth
\stopverb}

\p{If a deletion fails, report the error and continue with remaining deletions.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 6: Report}
\pre{\startverb
## Cleanup Complete

### Deleted
- fix/typo
- feature/login
- feature/api
- feature/api-v2
- feature/api-refactor
- feature/api-final
- Worktree: ../proj-auth

### Remaining (4 branches)
| Branch | Status |
|--------|--------|
| main | current |
| wip/new-feature | active work |
| experiment/old | needs review |
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Safety Rules}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Never invoke automatically} - Only run when user explicitly uses \code{\startverb /git-cleanup\stopverb}}
\li{\strong{Two confirmation gates only} - Analysis review, then deletion confirmation}
\li{\strong{Use correct delete command} - \code{\startverb -d\stopverb} for merged, \code{\startverb -D\stopverb} for squash-merged/superseded}
\li{\strong{Never touch protected branches} - main, master, develop, release/* (filtered programmatically)}
\li{\strong{Block dirty worktree removal} - Refuse without explicit data loss acknowledgment}
\li{\strong{Group related branches} - Don't scatter them across categories}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Rationalizations to Reject}
\p{These are common shortcuts that lead to data loss. Reject them:}

\pre{\startverb
| Rationalization | Why It's Wrong |
|-----------------|----------------|
| "The branch is old, it's probably safe to delete" | Age doesn't indicate merge status. Old branches may contain unmerged work. |
| "I can recover from reflog if needed" | Reflog entries expire. Users often don't know how to use reflog. Don't rely on it as a safety net. |
| "It's just a local branch, nothing important" | Local branches may contain the only copy of work not pushed anywhere. |
| "The PR was merged, so the branch is safe" | Squash merges don't preserve branch history. Verify the *specific* commits were incorporated. |
| "I'll just delete all the `[gone]` branches" | `[gone]` only means the remote was deleted. The local branch may have unpushed commits. |
| "The user seems to want everything deleted" | Always present analysis first. Let the user choose what to delete. |
| "The branch has commits not in main, so it has unpushed work" | "Not in main" ≠ "not pushed". A branch can be synced with its remote but not merged to main. Always check `git log origin/<branch>..<branch>`. |
\stopverb}
}
}